				\begin{document}$$R_{\text {p}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M62"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq29.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is the UMI pseudo-reference vector of control samples for the region <inline-formula id="IEq30"><alternatives><tex-math id="M63">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M64"><mml:mi>p</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq30.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
      <p id="Par52">A Gaussian mixture model with one to three mixture components is estimated from <inline-formula id="IEq31"><alternatives><tex-math id="M65">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$L_{\text {p}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M66"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq31.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> using <italic>Mclust</italic> function of R package mclust [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR16">16</xref>]. The estimated gaussian closest to <inline-formula id="IEq32"><alternatives><tex-math id="M67">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\widehat{L^{\text {UMI}}}=0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M68"><mml:mrow><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:msup><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msup><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq32.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is used to center the signal by subtracting its average from the <inline-formula id="IEq33"><alternatives><tex-math id="M69">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$L_{\text {p}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M70"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq33.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> values. Indeed, we assume that the Gaussian of our signal closest to 0 corresponds to a diploid state. This centering step could be disabled via the program’s arguments.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="Sec13">
      <title>Segmentation</title>
      <p id="Par53">Each gene is composed of <italic>n</italic> consecutive regions and we define a vector of log-ratios <inline-formula id="IEq34"><alternatives><tex-math id="M71">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$V_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M72"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>V</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq34.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> used for segmentation, as:<disp-formula id="Equ5"><alternatives><tex-math id="M73">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} V_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}} = \left\{ L_{\text {p}}^{\text {UMI}} ; L_{\text {p+1}}^{\text {UMI}} ; \cdots {}\right\} (p \in n) \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M74" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>V</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfenced close="}" open="{"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>;</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p+1</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>;</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mrow/></mml:mfenced><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>p</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_Equ5.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>mCNA uses the circular binary segmentation (CBS) method implemented in the R package PSCBS [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR17">17</xref>] to segment <inline-formula id="IEq35"><alternatives><tex-math id="M75">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$V_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M76"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>V</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq35.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
      <p id="Par54">To avoid breakpoints at outlier values, a vector of weights <inline-formula id="IEq36"><alternatives><tex-math id="M77">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$W$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M78"><mml:mi>W</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq36.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is given to CBS segmentation function. <inline-formula id="IEq37"><alternatives><tex-math id="M79">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$W$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M80"><mml:mi>W</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq37.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is inversely proportional to the variances of <inline-formula id="IEq38"><alternatives><tex-math id="M81">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$C_{\text {p}}^{\text {UMI}}/U$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M82"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>C</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">/</mml:mo><mml:mi>U</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq38.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> observed in the control samples and defined as:<disp-formula id="Equ6"><alternatives><tex-math id="M83">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} W_{\text {p}}=\frac{1}{var(M_{\text {p}}^{\text {UMI}}/U)} ( \text {within controls}) \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M84" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mi>v</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>M</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">/</mml:mo><mml:mi>U</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mtext>within controls</mml:mtext><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_Equ6.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula><inline-formula id="IEq39"><alternatives><tex-math id="M85">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${W_{\text {p}}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M86"><mml:msub><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq39.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> are then transformed to be limited to the interval [0,1] as follows:<disp-formula id="Equ7"><alternatives><tex-math id="M87">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} W'_{\text {p}} = \frac{ W_{\text {p}} - min(W_{\text {p}}) }{ max(W_{\text {p}}) - min(W_{\text {p}}) } \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M88" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext><mml:mo>′</mml:mo></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:msub><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>W</mml:mi><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_Equ7.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>Finally, a Student’s t-test is performed on each segmented region to test whether or not the <inline-formula id="IEq40"><alternatives><tex-math id="M89">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$V_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M90"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>V</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq40.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> vector is significantly different from the reference value of 0. To avoid false positive segments, a FDR correction is applied.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="Sec14">
      <title>Estimation of tumoral content</title>
      <p id="Par55">We define <inline-formula id="IEq41"><alternatives><tex-math id="M91">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$G_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M92"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq41.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq42"><alternatives><tex-math id="M93">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M94"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq42.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> the vectors <inline-formula id="IEq43"><alternatives><tex-math id="M95">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$V_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M96"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>V</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq43.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> of significant amplified/deleted segments, respectively. We use <inline-formula id="IEq44"><alternatives><tex-math id="M97">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M98"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq44.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and <inline-formula id="IEq45"><alternatives><tex-math id="M99">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$G_{\text {n}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M100"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>G</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>n</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq45.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> distributions to estimate tumor enrichment assuming that means of these distributions reflect a gain/loss of one segment copy and that log-ratios are a mixture of both tumoral and normal signals. We define as <inline-formula id="IEq46"><alternatives><tex-math id="M101">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$c$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M102"><mml:mi>c</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq46.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> the percentage of tumor enrichment to estimate.</p>
      <p id="Par56">Two independent estimates of <inline-formula id="IEq47"><alternatives><tex-math id="M103">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$c$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M104"><mml:mi>c</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq47.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> were produced: one from the significantly deleted segments and the other from those amplified. The estimation of <inline-formula id="IEq48"><alternatives><tex-math id="M105">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$c$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M106"><mml:mi>c</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq48.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> cannot be done in one step because log-ratios involving one gain or one loss are not symmetrical. For example, the loss of one copy of a segment in a sample containing only tumor cells will lead to a log-ratio equal to <inline-formula id="IEq49"><alternatives><tex-math id="M107">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\log _2(\frac{1}{2})=-1$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M108"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mo>log</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mfrac><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq49.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> while a gain of one copy will lead to <inline-formula id="IEq50"><alternatives><tex-math id="M109">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\log _2(\frac{3}{2})=0.58$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M110"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mo>log</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>3</mml:mn><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mfrac><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.58</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq50.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
      <p id="Par57">From amplified regions, the distribution of <inline-formula id="IEq51"><alternatives><tex-math id="M111">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$L_{\text {p}}^{\text {UMI}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M112"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>L</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mtext>p</mml:mtext></mml:mrow><mml:mtext>UMI</mml:mtext></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2021_4060_Article_IEq51.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> can be decomposed as follows:<disp-formula id="Equ1"><label>1</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M113">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
